"""
MKT Context Commentary — Hebrews chapters 6–9 (gap-fill pass)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-hebrews-6-9-gaps.py

Key decisions:
- ch6: Apostasy warning in context of Roman persecution and religio licita privilege
- ch7: Levitical tithe law, priestly genealogy, honor-through-tithing in ANE context
- ch8: Jeremiah 31 in its exile context; Qumran new covenant self-understanding
- ch9: Tabernacle furnishings from Exod/Lev; Mishnah Yoma Yom Kippur detail
- ch9:16-17 diatheke as will in Hellenistic testamentary law (exploits double meaning)
- ch9:28 Isaiah 53 Servant echo and the parousia as high priest's post-atonement reappearance
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / source / f"{book}.json"
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / source / f"{book}.json"
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f"  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}")

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

HEBREWS = json.loads(r"""
{
  "6": {
    "1": "<p>The \"elementary teaching about Christ\" that the author urges the community to move beyond reflects a structured Jewish-Christian catechetical curriculum. Early Christian communities, many of them organized around former synagogue members, developed initiation catechesis that adapted Jewish patterns of instruction. The Damascus Document from Qumran shows a structured induction process for new community members; rabbinic literature describes the staged instruction of proselytes. The six items listed in 6:1-2 (repentance from dead works, faith in God, baptisms, laying on of hands, resurrection of the dead, eternal judgment) correspond closely to Jewish conversion requirements adapted for the Christian context, suggesting the audience knew this curriculum well.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The plural \"baptisms\" (Greek <em>baptismōn</em>, literally \"washings\") reflects the complex baptismal landscape of the first century. Jewish purification rites included multiple ritual immersions: the proselyte's full-body immersion on conversion, the Levitical purification immersions (Lev 14-15), the priestly immersion on the Day of Atonement (Mishnah Yoma 3:3), the Qumran community's daily immersions, and John's baptism. Early Christian communities had to distinguish their baptism from these alternatives. \"Laying on of hands\" (semikhah) was a Jewish ordination gesture used for priests, prophets, and Torah authorities (Num 27:18-23; Deut 34:9); the Christian community applied it to Spirit-conferral, healing, and commissioning. \"Resurrection of the dead and eternal judgment\" were points of Jewish theological controversy — the Pharisees affirmed resurrection against the Sadducees' denial (Acts 23:6-8; Josephus, Jewish War 2.163-165).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The parenthetical \"if God permits\" (ean epitrepē ho theos) reflects the Jewish piety of acknowledging divine sovereignty over human plans. The phrase is virtually the Hebrew <em>b'ezrat hashem</em> (\"with God's help\") or the Arabic <em>inshallah</em>: a routine acknowledgment that human intentions are contingent on divine will. James 4:13-15 reflects the same piety in a NT context. Philo uses similar language throughout his works when proposing theological explanations. The conciseness of the phrase (just three Greek words) suggests it was a recognized formula rather than a developed theological statement — the audience would hear it as standard Jewish-Christian piety acknowledging that even pastoral-pedagogical progress depends on divine enablement.</p>",
    "5": "<p>\"The powers of the coming age\" (dynameis mellontos aiōnos) reflects the Jewish two-age eschatological framework: the present age (ha-olam ha-zeh) marked by suffering, exile, and incompleteness, and the age to come (ha-olam ha-ba) marked by resurrection, justice, and divine rule. The Dead Sea Scrolls describe the coming age in terms of cosmic transformation; 4 Ezra and 2 Baruch (both roughly contemporary with Hebrews) meditate extensively on when and how the new age will dawn. The claim that the community has already \"tasted\" (experientially touched) the powers of this coming age is an eschatological claim: the age has not yet fully arrived but its power has broken into the present. This \"already-not-yet\" eschatological structure was characteristic of early Christian experience (cf. 2 Cor 5:17; Eph 1:14).</p>",
    "6": "<p>The apostasy warning of 6:4-6 is best understood in its specific social-historical context. Jewish Christians who faced Roman persecution (under Nero, 64 CE; under Domitian, 81-96 CE) could avoid legal trouble by returning to the synagogue: Judaism was a <em>religio licita</em> (legally recognized religion) with exemptions from emperor-cult requirements. The synagogue community would have welcomed back those who had strayed into the Jesus-movement, and returning would restore social and legal security. Hebrews' warning that such return constitutes \"crucifying the Son of God all over again\" frames the apostasy in terms of the public honor-shame system: to return to a community that had condemned Jesus (and might still mock his crucifixion as shameful) was to align oneself publicly with the crucifiers' verdict.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The agricultural metaphor of rain falling on land draws on Palestinian agricultural realities. Israel's climate was characterized by two rainy seasons (the early or autumn rain, <em>yōreh</em>, and the late or spring rain, <em>malkōsh</em>) that were understood as divine blessings for covenant faithfulness (Deut 11:14; Joel 2:23). The land's response to rain — producing useful crops or thorns — was the relevant variable, not the rain itself. Deut 11:17 and Lev 26:4 connect rainfall to covenant obedience: the same rain that blessed the faithful would be withheld from the faithless. The agricultural image was immediately intelligible to a community with Palestinian roots or knowledge of the Pentateuch's agricultural covenant-language.</p>",
    "8": "<p>\"Thorns and thistles\" evoke Genesis 3:17-18, where thorns and thistles are the specific vegetation of the cursed ground after Adam's expulsion from Eden. The land that produces thorns is returning to its pre-redemptive state — the state of the fallen creation rather than the blessed land of the covenant. The \"burning\" at the end may recall Deuteronomy 29:23 (the description of cursed land that is \"burned with sulfur and salt\") and the prophetic judgment oracles (Isa 9:18-19; Isa 10:17-18) where fire is the instrument of divine judgment. For a Jewish audience with rich connections to the land-theology of Deuteronomy, the burnt-thorns image carried connotations of covenant curse and divine judgment.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The sudden shift from warning to pastoral encouragement reflects the rhetorical pattern of the Jewish homily. The author uses the midrashic technique of presenting a severe warning then immediately softening it with words of encouragement — a technique designed to convict without crushing. The address \"dear friends\" (agapētoi, beloved) signals the shift; the use of this affectionate term in the NT is typically associated with pastoral warmth and encouragement (Rom 12:19; 1 Cor 10:14; 2 Cor 7:1). The phrase \"we are convinced of better things in your case\" (pepeismetha de peri hymōn ta kreissona) is a rhetorical act of positive expectation that itself functions to encourage — the speaker's confidence becomes a resource for the community's confidence.</p>",
    "10": "<p>\"The love you have shown him as you have helped his people\" refers to the community's concrete acts of service and solidarity. Acts of charity and community service (tzedakah, righteous giving) were central to Jewish communal ethics — Pirkei Avot 1:2 lists the world as standing on three things: Torah, worship, and acts of lovingkindness. The Qumran community had a common treasury and pooled resources. Early Christian communities developed similar mutual-aid networks (Acts 2:44-45; 4:34-37; 2 Cor 8-9). The \"helped his people\" (diakonēsantes tois hagiois) likely refers to practical support of traveling missionaries or of community members in prison or need — the same ministry that Romans 16 and 1 Corinthians 16 document in other communities.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The call to \"show this same diligence to the very end, in order to make your hope sure\" reflects the Jewish covenant ideal of lifetime faithfulness. Deuteronomy's emphasis on \"observe... keep... do\" throughout one's life (Deut 5:1; 6:24-25; 7:11-12) and the Psalter's affirmation of the one who walks blamelessly throughout life (Ps 15; 24) provide the biblical pattern. The Qumran community required annual renewal of covenant commitment (1QS 2:19-25) and monitored members' ongoing fidelity. The emphasis on endurance to \"the very end\" (achri telous) reflects the specific pastoral problem of the letter: the community had begun well but was in danger of not finishing.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The call to imitate those \"who through faith and patience inherit what has been promised\" introduces the faith-catalogue of ch. 11. The concept of exemplary ancestors as models for imitation was standard in both Jewish and Greco-Roman ethical instruction. Sirach 44-50 (the \"Praise of Famous Men\") celebrates Israel's ancestors as models of various virtues. Philo devoted entire treatises to Abraham, Moses, and Joseph as exemplary figures. The Testaments of the Twelve Patriarchs present the patriarchs as models of virtue and vice for their descendants. The Greco-Roman tradition similarly celebrated illustrious ancestors (Livy's purpose in writing Roman history was to provide moral exemplars). The audience expected to learn from their ancestors' example — Hebrews builds on this expectation in its extended faith-catalogue.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The citation of Genesis 22:17 (\"I will surely bless you and give you many descendants\") comes from the Aqedah (binding of Isaac) narrative, which was the most celebrated act of Abraham's faith in Jewish tradition. The Aqedah was central to Jewish liturgy and theology: the Mishnah (Rosh Hashanah 16a) records that the Shofar (ram's horn) blown on Rosh Hashanah was meant to invoke God's memory of the ram substituted for Isaac; the Amidah prayer includes a petition that God remember the Aqedah's merit for Israel. Jubilees 17-18 and 4 Maccabees 16:20 celebrate Abraham's willingness to sacrifice Isaac as the supreme test of covenant loyalty. The oath sworn by God at the Aqedah was therefore the most solemn and significant divine promise in the Jewish tradition.</p>",
    "15": "<p>\"After waiting patiently, Abraham received what was promised\" describes the gap between the promise (Gen 12, 15, 17) and the fulfillment. The birth of Isaac came approximately 25 years after the initial promise (Gen 12:1-3 → Gen 21:1-3). Jewish tradition celebrated Abraham's patience through this long period of waiting as one of his ten trials (Pirkei Avot 5:3 lists ten tests through which Abraham was tried). The word \"patient\" translates the Greek <em>makrothymia</em> — the \"long-temperedness\" or sustained endurance that does not capitulate to impatience. The contrast with Esau (Heb 12:16-17), who could not wait even the time it took to prepare a meal and sold his birthright, gives Abraham's decades of patient waiting its rhetorical force as a counter-example.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Oath-taking customs in first-century Judaism and the Greco-Roman world provide the background for this verse. In Jewish law (Shevu'ot 4:13), an oath sworn by God's name or by heaven and earth was absolutely binding; false oaths were severe violations (Lev 19:12; Exod 20:7). The Essenes reportedly refused to take oaths because they regarded their word as more reliable than an oath — but this was an exceptional position. In Hellenistic commercial and legal practice, oaths were used routinely in contracts, court testimony, and treaty-making, invoking divine witnesses to guarantee truthfulness. The principle that the oath \"ends all argument\" (pases antilogias peras) reflects the legal reality that an oath-supported claim was the highest available form of attestation and could not ordinarily be challenged further.</p>",
    "17": "<p>God's use of an oath to confirm the promise to Abraham (Gen 22:16: \"by myself I have sworn\") was interpreted in Jewish tradition as an act of divine condescension to human weakness — God does not need to swear, since his word is absolutely reliable, but swears for the sake of those who need the added assurance. Philo (On the Sacrifices of Abel and Cain 93-94) makes exactly this argument: God swears not because he might be untrustworthy but because the human mind needs the extra reassurance. The \"heirs of the promise\" (klēronomous tēs epangelias) would have been understood by the Jewish-Christian audience as themselves — those who, through faith in the Messiah, have been grafted into the Abrahamic promise (cf. Gal 3:29).</p>",
    "18": "<p>The \"city of refuge\" metaphor implicit in the phrase \"we who have fled to take hold of the hope\" draws on the OT institution of the cities of refuge (Num 35:9-28; Deut 4:41-43; 19:1-13; Josh 20). The six cities of refuge were designated places where someone who had accidentally committed manslaughter could flee and be protected from the blood-avenger until the case was heard. Philo (On Flight and Finding 75-118) allegorizes the cities of refuge extensively as stages of the soul's journey toward God. The Christian community's confident hope is like a refugee who has reached the safety of the city — the protection is real and the pursuer cannot reach them there.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The term \"forerunner\" (<em>prodromos</em>) was used in several technical senses in the Greco-Roman world: the military scout who went ahead to reconnoiter enemy terrain; the first ship into harbor that guided others to safety; the firstfruits of the harvest that inaugurated the rest. In the athletic context of Hebrews 12:1-2, it denotes the runner who enters the finish area first, paving the way for others. The Qumran community understood certain figures (the Teacher of Righteousness, or Elijah) as forerunners of the messianic age. The specific claim that the forerunner has entered \"into the inner place behind the curtain\" places the image in the Yom Kippur context: the high priest entering the Most Holy Place was the supreme priestly act of the year. Jesus as prodromos into the heavenly sanctuary is the pioneer-priest whose entry prepares the way for the community's own eventual entry.</p>"
  },
  "7": {
    "2": "<p>The etymology of Melchizedek as \"king of righteousness\" (<em>melek</em> = king + <em>tsedeq</em> = righteousness) and Salem as \"peace\" (<em>shalom</em>) reflects the Jewish practice of finding theological meaning in proper names. This form of biblical interpretation (etymology as theology) appears extensively in Philo (On the Cherubim 99; Allegorical Laws 3.79-82), where the meanings of Hebrew names unlock their spiritual significance. The identification of Salem with Jerusalem was standard in Jewish tradition (Ps 76:2: \"His abode has been established in Salem, his dwelling place in Zion\"; Josephus, Jewish War 6.438). By combining \"king of righteousness\" and \"king of peace,\" Hebrews creates a profile that resonated with messianic expectations from Isaiah 9:6-7 (\"Prince of Peace\") and the Psalms of Solomon 17:35 (the Davidic king who rules with righteousness and peace).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The argument from Melchizedek's textual profile in Genesis — no father, no mother, no genealogy, no birth, no death recorded — reflects the Jewish interpretive principle that the Torah's silences are as theologically significant as its statements. Rabbinic hermeneutics formalized this as the principle <em>ein mukdam u-me'uchar b'Torah</em> (there is no necessary chronological order in the Torah) and the corresponding attention to what is <em>not</em> said (e.g., the Mishnah's discussion of why the Torah begins with creation rather than the first commandment). The 11QMelchizedek text from Qumran treated Melchizedek's indefinite profile as evidence of his heavenly nature. Hebrews reads the same textual silence differently: not as evidence of heavenly nature but as a designed typological pattern pointing toward the Son's eternal priesthood.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The honor conferred by Abraham giving a tithe to Melchizedek is intelligible within the honor-exchange economy of the ancient world. Tithing in the ancient Near East was not only a religious obligation but an acknowledgment of superior status and authority. The tribute paid to a conquering king or a recognized superior was expressed through gifts of first-fruits, tithes, and offerings. Genesis 14's narrative of Abraham returning from his victory over the four kings presents Abraham at the height of his military prestige; the patriarch who had just defeated kings gives a tithe to Melchizedek. The argument's force depends on the audience's recognition that tithing-as-honor was a culturally universal acknowledgment of the tithe-receiver's superiority.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Numbers 18:21-32 established the Levitical tithe: the people gave a tithe to the Levites for their service at the tabernacle; the Levites in turn gave a tithe of the tithe to the priests. The system created a financial support structure for the Temple cult that was deeply embedded in the social and economic life of Judea and the diaspora. By the first century, the tithe collection had become a complex and sometimes contentious institution (Josephus, Antiquities 20.181, records violent disputes between high priests and lower clergy over the tithes). The rabbinic literature devotes multiple tractates (Maa'serot, Maa'ser Sheni, Bikkurim) to the details of the tithe laws. Hebrews' audience would know the tithe system not as abstract law but as a practical institution governing the priestly economy.</p>",
    "6": "<p>\"This man did not trace his descent from Levi\" places Melchizedek outside the entire Levitical genealogical structure that governed priestly legitimacy in Israel. Priestly genealogy was not merely a legal formality but a social institution of enormous practical importance: priests who could not prove their genealogy were excluded from service (Ezra 2:61-63; Neh 7:63-65). The discovery of disqualifying genealogy could end a priestly career. Josephus (Against Apion 1.28-36) describes the elaborate record-keeping system that maintained priestly pedigrees across generations, even in the diaspora. The assertion that Melchizedek received tithes from Abraham without any Levitical genealogy is therefore a claim that a different principle of priestly legitimacy operates in his case — one that precedes and transcends the Mosaic-genealogical system.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The principle that \"the lesser is blessed by the greater\" was embedded in the social logic of blessing in the ancient world. Patriarchal blessings in Genesis (12:2-3; 24:60; 27:27-40; 49:1-28) were understood as effective speech-acts that transferred destiny and status — the blessed received a share in the blesser's power and favor. In Jewish legal and social thought, the ability to bless implied authority over the one blessed. The high priest blessed the people after the Yom Kippur service (Mishnah Yoma 7:1); the Levitical blessing (Num 6:22-27) placed the divine name on Israel. For an audience that understood blessing as a power-conferral, the observation that Melchizedek blessed Abraham (rather than the reverse) was a decisive argument about relative status.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The contrast between \"people who die\" collecting tithes and one \"who is testified to be living\" collecting tithes reflects the argument from textual attestation. The Levitical priests are historically verifiable as mortal — their deaths, successions, and genealogies are recorded throughout Chronicles, Ezra-Nehemiah, and Josephus. Melchizedek's \"living\" status is a negative attestation: since Scripture records no death for him, the text itself bears witness to his living. This interpretive move — treating textual silence about death as positive testimony to life — is characteristic of Jewish midrashic exegesis. The Targums and rabbinic literature occasionally reason from the absence of a death notice to the conclusion that a figure was translated (as Elijah) or lives still.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The argument that Levi \"paid tithes through Abraham\" depends on the concept of corporate generational identity — the notion that the ancestor's actions can be attributed to his descendants because they existed, in some sense, within him. This concept appears in Jewish interpretation of the Aqedah (the merit of Abraham's faithfulness benefits his descendants) and in Paul's argument in Romans 5 that all humanity sinned \"in Adam.\" The specific argument here — that Levi was \"in the body of\" (or \"in the loins of\") his ancestor Abraham — reflects the Jewish understanding of seminal causality, in which the ancestor's physical body contained within it all his biological descendants. This was not merely metaphor but a serious anthropological claim about corporate identity across generations.</p>",
    "10": "<p>\"Levi was still in the body of his ancestor\" describes the generational distance between Abraham and his great-grandson Levi (Abraham → Isaac → Jacob → Levi — three generations). The Genesis genealogy (Gen 29:34; 35:23; 46:11) establishes this lineage clearly. In ANE genealogical thinking, the descendants of a patriarch shared in his representative acts because they shared his biological identity — the patriarch stood for all who would come from him. This is the same framework that enables the promise to Abraham to benefit all his physical and spiritual descendants. Hebrews' use of this framework is unusual in applying it to Levi's subordination rather than to his honor — typically the patriarchal narrative was invoked to claim honor for descendants, not to establish their inferiority.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The connection between the priesthood and the Torah reflects the structural reality of the Mosaic legal code: a very large portion of the Torah (Exodus 25-40; Leviticus; significant portions of Numbers) consists of regulations specifically governing the Levitical priestly service. If the priesthood is changed, the entire legal apparatus built around it — the sacrificial system, the purity laws, the Temple service — is also necessarily changed. This was not a peripheral implication but a radical claim: the Torah as a whole was organized around the Levitical priesthood, so a change in priesthood entails a change in the legal structure. Jewish Christians who wanted to maintain Torah observance while accepting Jesus as Messiah faced exactly this structural problem, which Hebrews addresses directly.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Jesus's descent from Judah was a fact that the Jewish-Christian community both celebrated (as fulfilling Davidic messianic expectations) and had to reckon with theologically. The tribe of Judah had no priestly standing in the Torah: Leviticus 21-22 restricted priestly service to the descendants of Aaron (from the tribe of Levi); the tribe of Judah provided the royal line but not the priestly line. Numbers 3:10 explicitly excluded non-Aaronides from priestly service under pain of death. When Uzziah king of Judah attempted to offer incense in the Temple (2 Chr 26:16-21), he was struck with leprosy — the violation of tribal boundaries in the priestly sphere was a serious sacrilege. Jesus's Judahite descent was therefore a theological problem, not a minor detail, in any claim to priestly status.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The \"clear\" descent of Jesus from Judah reflects the genealogical traditions preserved in Matthew 1 and Luke 3, but also the widely shared knowledge in the Jewish-Christian community that Jesus was a Galilean from the Davidic line (cf. Mark 10:47-48; Rom 1:3). The Davidic genealogy was central to messianic identification: Psalms of Solomon 17:21 calls for the Lord to \"raise up for them a king, the son of David\"; 4QFlorilegium interprets 2 Samuel 7:14 as predicting the Davidic branch who would arise in the last days. The rabbinic tradition (b. Sanhedrin 98b) preserves discussions about the Messiah's Davidic origin. Judah's complete exclusion from priestly function in the Torah is the foil against which Hebrews argues that Jesus's priesthood must be of a fundamentally different, non-Mosaic type.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The comparison \"another priest like Melchizedek appears\" reflects the expectation of a renewed or heightened priestly figure in Jewish eschatological thought. Testament of Levi 18 describes an eschatological priest who will arise in the last days with unprecedented holiness and authority — this priest will open the gates of paradise, remove the sword of Eden, and give the saints to eat of the tree of life. 11QMelchizedek describes Melchizedek as the eschatological figure who will execute judgment and proclaim liberation. The Qumran community's expectation of a Priestly Messiah alongside the Davidic Messiah shows the currency of heightened priestly expectations. Hebrews argues that Jesus's appearance as a Melchizedek-order priest fulfills these eschatological priestly expectations.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The contrast between \"a regulation about ancestry\" (entolē sarkinē, literally a fleshly commandment) and \"the power of an indestructible life\" maps onto a fundamental distinction in Jewish theology between external, bodily qualifications for the priesthood (Leviticus 21's list of physical requirements: no blindness, lameness, broken limbs, etc.) and the inner spiritual fitness that the prophets increasingly emphasized. The prophetic critique of purely external religion (Isa 1:11-17; Jer 7:21-23; Amos 5:21-24; Mic 6:6-8) provided conceptual resources for distinguishing bodily-genealogical fitness from genuine divine calling. Philo (On the Special Laws 1.107-119) argues at length that the high priest must have internal moral qualifications that exceed the external bodily requirements.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The repetition of Psalm 110:4 (\"You are a priest forever, in the order of Melchizedek\") as a formal divine attestation (\"For it is declared,\" martyreitai) reflects the legal weight given to scriptural citation in Jewish argumentation. The Psalms as divine speech — a principle embedded in the phrase \"The LORD says to my lord\" (Ps 110:1) — made Psalm citations function as divine testimony rather than human opinion. The rabbis used scriptural citations to settle legal disputes (the principle of <em>d'orayta</em> — a Torah teaching as opposed to a rabbinic interpretation — carried binding authority). Hebrews' use of Ps 110:4 as a formal divine declaration provides the authoritative textual ground for the entire priesthood-change argument.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The language of \"setting aside\" (athetēsis) the former regulation evoked Jewish legal categories for invalidating a law or legal ruling. In Greek legal practice, <em>athetēsis</em> meant the formal annulment of a document or agreement. The question of which laws could be set aside, and by whom, was intensely contested in first-century Judaism. The Qumran community considered themselves living by a stricter interpretation of Torah that corrected the Jerusalem establishment's corruptions; the Pharisees debated with Sadducees and other groups about oral law's authority. The claim that a Mosaic regulation could be set aside by divine oracle was a theologically radical move — the very character of Torah as divine, permanent law seemed to preclude it.</p>",
    "19": "<p>\"The law made nothing perfect\" was a claim that engaged directly with one of the most cherished Jewish theological convictions: that Torah observance was the path to covenant standing before God. The Psalms celebrate Torah as perfect, reliable, and life-giving (Ps 19:7-11; 119:1-176). Ben Sira 17:11 equates the gift of Torah with eternal life. The book of Jubilees presents Torah observance as the fundamental mark of covenant Israel, kept even by the angels in heaven. Hebrews' claim that Torah \"made nothing perfect\" was therefore not a minor qualification but a direct challenge to this entire framework — the claim is not that Torah was wrong but that it was structurally incomplete, designed to point toward but not achieve the final goal (telos) of the relationship with God.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The contrast between priests ordained \"without an oath\" and Jesus ordained \"with an oath\" reflects the legal weight that oaths carried in appointment ceremonies. Levitical priests were ordained through the ritual described in Exodus 28-29 and Leviticus 8-9 — elaborate rituals involving anointing, clothing, sacrifice, and the application of blood, but no oath from God specifically confirming the individual priest's appointment. The high priestly ordination described in the Mishnah (Yoma 1-2) required extensive preparation and prayer but did not include a divine oath backing the appointment. The divine oath of Psalm 110:4 thus provides a form of appointment-legitimation that the entire history of Levitical ordination could not claim.</p>",
    "21": "<p>\"The Lord has sworn and will not change his mind\" (Ps 110:4) reflects the absolute irrevocability of divine oaths in Jewish theology. Numbers 23:19 states that \"God is not human, that he should lie, not a human being, that he should change his mind\" — a text that directly addresses the impossibility of divine oath-reversal. In contrast, human priestly appointments were quite reversible: the Hasmonean period saw the high priesthood change hands multiple times; Herod the Great appointed and dismissed high priests according to political convenience; the Romans continued this practice. Against this background of arbitrary, revocable priestly appointments, the divine oath sworn by Ps 110:4 represents an appointment that no subsequent political calculation can revoke.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The list of high priests from Aaron's appointment to the Temple's destruction illustrates the mortality problem concretely. The book of Chronicles preserves a list of Aaronic high priests, and Josephus (Antiquities 20.224-251) provides a fuller list: 83 high priests from Aaron to the Temple's destruction in 70 CE. The rapid turnover of the Second Temple period was particularly striking: Josephus lists 28 high priests in the last century before the Temple's fall, many serving very brief terms due to political appointment and dismissal. The instability of the historical high priesthood gave the argument about mortality a contemporary edge — the audience had likely witnessed the chaotic priestly succession of their own era.</p>",
    "24": "<p>A \"permanent\" (aparabatos) priesthood was precisely what the Jewish world lacked. The ideal of a stable, legitimate, enduring high priesthood was a religious aspiration frustrated by the historical realities of Hellenistic and Roman-period Judaism. The Zadokite high priests were displaced by the Hasmoneans in 152 BCE; the Hasmoneans were displaced by Herod's appointments; various priestly families (the houses of Boethus, Phiabi, Annas) traded the office under Roman oversight. The Qumran community's longing for the restoration of the legitimate Zadokite high priesthood (reflected in multiple DSS texts) was one response to this instability. Hebrews addresses the same longing with a different answer: not the restoration of Zadokite legitimacy but the appointment of a priest whose life cannot end.</p>",
    "25": "<p>\"He always lives to make intercession for them\" positions the risen Christ as the permanent heavenly intercessor. In Jewish angelology and heavenly court theology, the archangels functioned as intercessors before the divine throne: 1 Enoch 9:1-11 describes the archangels presenting the prayers of the righteous before God; Testament of Levi 3:5-6 describes Levi offering incense as intercessory service for all the ignorance-sins of Israel. The Day of Atonement's incense-burning in the Most Holy Place was understood as creating the cloud that protected Israel before the divine throne (Lev 16:12-13). Hebrews transposes this intercessory function from the annual high-priestly act to the continuous heavenly intercession of the risen Son — a permanent intercessory presence that the annual ritual was designed to symbolize.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The description of the ideal high priest — \"holy, blameless, pure, set apart from sinners, exalted above the heavens\" — reflects the qualifications prescribed in Leviticus 21 and idealized in Second Temple literature. Leviticus 21:16-23 lists the physical disqualifications for priestly service; Leviticus 22:1-16 addresses ritual purity requirements. The Mishnah tractate Yoma describes the moral and ritual preparation of the high priest in the days before Yom Kippur: he was separated from his family, kept awake by the elders who feared he might become ritually impure through sexual dreams, and instructed in the exact ritual sequence. All of this elaborate preparation addressed a fundamental problem that Hebrews claims is resolved in the Son: the high priest was himself a sinner who needed his own atonement before he could represent others.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The Day of Atonement sequence described in Leviticus 16 and elaborated in Mishnah Yoma required the high priest to first offer a bull for himself and his household, then a goat for the people. The Mishnah (Yoma 4:2; 6:2) preserves the precise order and the prescribed confessional prayers for each offering. This double offering (self, then people) was the structural feature that distinguished the Yom Kippur from other sacrifices and that most visibly illustrated the high priest's own sinfulness. Philo (On Special Laws 1.226-241) argues that the high priest's own moral preparation was as important as the sacrificial ritual itself. Hebrews' claim that Jesus offered \"once for all when he offered himself\" compresses the two-stage offering into one: the self-offering replaces both stages.</p>",
    "28": "<p>\"The oath, which came after the law, appointed the Son\" reflects a Jewish hermeneutical principle about the temporal order of canonical texts: a later text can supersede or qualify an earlier one. The principle was contested — the Sadducees argued that only the written Torah (not later prophetic or wisdom texts) had binding authority; the Pharisees accepted the authority of the Oral Torah alongside the Written Torah. In Hebrews' argument, Psalm 110 (attributed to David, after the Mosaic period) is used to show that the Mosaic priestly system was always provisional: the oracle sworn in Psalm 110 points beyond the Levitical arrangement to a different order. The \"came after the law\" sequencing was therefore not accidental but divinely designed — God delayed the Psalm 110 promise to signal its eschatological rather than Mosaic character.</p>"
  },
  "8": {
    "1": "<p>\"Now the main point of what we are saying is this\" (kephalaion) introduces the theological summit of the letter: the seated high priest in the heavenly sanctuary. In Greek rhetorical practice, the <em>kephalaion</em> was the summary-statement that captured the argument's essence. The posture of the seated high priest — addressed previously in 1:3 (\"sat down at the right hand of the Majesty\") and developed here — reflects the Yom Kippur background: no chairs were in the Tabernacle or Temple, because the priestly work was never done. The sitting marks completion. The audience familiar with the Temple's furniture would immediately grasp the theological weight: the seated position signals finished work, not waiting for the next ritual cycle.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The \"true tabernacle set up by the Lord\" draws on two traditions. First, Numbers 24:6 in the LXX uses the rare term for the \"tents that God planted\" — a possible reference that Hebrews takes as pointing to the heavenly sanctuary. Second, the widespread Jewish apocalyptic tradition of the heavenly sanctuary (already noted in 1 Enoch, Testament of Levi, 4Q405 Songs of the Sabbath Sacrifice) understood the earthly tabernacle/temple as a replica of the heavenly original. The Septuagint translation of Exodus 25:9 (\"according to all that I show you, the pattern of the tabernacle\") uses the word <em>paradeigma</em> (pattern, model) — Hebrews exploits this LXX translation to argue that the earthly structure was always a secondary, derivative version of the primary heavenly one.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The necessity that Jesus \"have something to offer\" reflects the Jewish understanding of the high priest as fundamentally a sacrificing officer. The entire Levitical system was built around the logic of sacrifice as the mechanism of divine-human reconciliation: where sin had created a breach in the covenant relationship, blood-offering repaired it (Lev 17:11: \"the life of the flesh is in the blood, and I have given it for you on the altar to make atonement for your souls\"). The high priest without a sacrifice was not a high priest at all — his entire function was defined by offering. The argument that Jesus must therefore have something to offer bridges the Jewish sacrificial logic and the Christian proclamation of the cross.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The observation that if Jesus were on earth he would not qualify as a priest addresses a practical argument his Jewish contemporaries could have raised: Jesus was a Galilean carpenter from the tribe of Judah, with no priestly credentials, who was crucified outside Jerusalem — how could he possibly be a high priest? The answer is that his priesthood operates in a different sphere entirely. The earthly Temple with its Levitical priests was still functioning during Jesus's ministry (and during most of Hebrews' composition period); Jesus's ministry did not compete with the Jerusalem cult on its own ground but operated in the heavenly sphere that the Jerusalem cult only shadowed. The earthly continuation of the Levitical system was therefore not evidence against Jesus's priesthood but evidence of its different order.</p>",
    "6": "<p>\"The ministry Jesus has received is as superior to theirs as the covenant of which he is mediator is better\" introduces the explicit covenant-comparison that the Jeremiah citation will develop. The concept of covenant as the structuring framework of divine-human relations was central to Jewish theology in the first century. The Sinai covenant defined Israel's identity, its legal obligations, and its relationship with God; the various renewal ceremonies (Deut 29-30; Josh 24; Neh 8-10) showed that covenant loyalty was not automatic but required constant maintenance. The Qumran community understood itself as having entered a new covenant in the Damascus period; early Christianity made the same claim in relation to Jesus's blood. Hebrews engages this covenant-comparison directly rather than avoiding it.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The rhetorical argument that \"if there had been nothing wrong with the first covenant, no place would have been sought for another\" uses the <em>a fortiori</em> logic that was standard in both Jewish and Hellenistic argumentation. In Jewish legal reasoning, the principle of <em>kal v'chomer</em> (light and heavy) was one of Hillel's seven hermeneutical rules: if something is true of the lesser case, how much more of the greater. Here the logic is retroactive: the existence of a new covenant promise implies the inadequacy of the first — God would not promise what was unnecessary. This same argument appears in Paul (Gal 3:21: \"if a law had been given that could impart life...\") and reflects a shared Jewish-Christian hermeneutical approach.</p>",
    "9": "<p>\"Not like the covenant I made with their ancestors when I took them by the hand to lead them out of Egypt\" (Jer 31:32) evokes the foundational Exodus narrative of covenant initiation. The hand-holding image (\"took them by the hand\") is an intimacy metaphor for the covenant relationship at its most personal — God as the parent leading a child. The Exodus redemption was the basis of the Sinai covenant (Exod 20:2: \"I am the LORD your God who brought you out of Egypt\") and the standard pattern that later redemptions were expected to mirror (Isa 43:16-21: the new Exodus). The covenant-breaking (\"they did not remain in my covenant\") refers to the entire trajectory from the golden calf incident through the cycles of idolatry that culminated in the Babylonian exile — a story of repeated covenant violation that Jeremiah witnessed in its final catastrophic chapter.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The promise of internalized law (\"I will put my laws in their minds and write them on their hearts\") reflects the prophetic critique of externalized religion. Jeremiah (17:1) had described Judah's sin as \"written with a pen of iron\" on their hearts — the heart that was inscribed with sin needed to be re-inscribed with Torah. Ezekiel 36:26-27 promises a new heart and spirit that will enable Torah-keeping from within. The contrast between the stone tablets of Sinai (exterior inscription) and the heart inscription of the new covenant invokes a transformation of the very organ of motivation. This internalized law was not a different Torah but the same Torah written in a new place — in the will and affections rather than only on external tablets, enabling the obedience that the Sinai generation had repeatedly failed to give.</p>",
    "11": "<p>\"No longer will they teach their neighbor, saying Know the Lord\" describes the transformation of how divine knowledge is transmitted. In the Sinai covenant structure, priests, prophets, scribes, and teachers mediated knowledge of God to the people — the Levitical priests were charged with instructing Israel in the Torah (Lev 10:11; Deut 33:10; Mal 2:7); the prophets spoke God's word; the scribes copied and interpreted Scripture; the synagogue teachers (later the rabbis) expounded. This entire system of mediated divine knowledge presupposed that most people needed trained intermediaries to know God. The new covenant promise describes a direct, unmediated knowing that transcends the educational hierarchy — from the least to the greatest, all will know God directly. This does not abolish teaching but transforms it from conveying knowledge of an unknown God to deepening knowledge of a God already personally known.</p>",
    "12": "<p>\"I will forgive their wickedness and will remember their sins no more\" is the culminating promise of Jeremiah 31:34 and the pivot of the entire new covenant oracle. The Day of Atonement provided annual forgiveness for the past year's sins but not permanent, unrepeatable forgiveness — the liturgical cycle required annual return to address new accumulation. The permanent divine forgetting promised in Jeremiah is qualitatively different: not an annual clearing of the slate but a final, irrevocable release from the accumulated record of sin. The Qumran community (Damascus Document 2:4-5; Community Rule 3:6-9) described the community's renewed covenant standing through a kind of ongoing divine mercy, but Hebrews reads Jeremiah's promise as pointing to a single, completed act of forgiveness that ends the cycle.</p>"
  },
  "9": {
    "2": "<p>The lampstand (Menorah) in the first room of the tabernacle was a seven-branched golden lamp described in Exodus 25:31-40. In Second Temple practice, the Menorah burned continuously and became one of the most recognized symbols of Jewish identity — Josephus (Jewish War 7.148) describes its image on the Arch of Titus in Rome, where it was displayed as war-spoil after Jerusalem's fall. The showbread (lechem ha-panim, bread of the presence) consisted of twelve loaves arranged on the golden table, replaced weekly on the Sabbath (Lev 24:5-9); the replaced loaves were eaten by the priests. These furnishings in the Holy Place (accessible to priests) contrasted with the absolute privacy of the Most Holy Place — the gradient of access to the divine presence was built into the sanctuary's physical architecture.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The second curtain (katapetasma) that separated the Holy Place from the Most Holy Place was the barrier described in Exodus 26:31-33 — made of blue, purple, and scarlet yarn and fine twisted linen, embroidered with cherubim. The Mishnah (Shekalim 8:4-5) records that the second Temple had two curtains, one cubit apart, with the priests entering from the south side and exiting from the north to avoid turning their backs to the sanctuary. The curtain's tearing at Jesus's crucifixion (Matt 27:51; Mark 15:38; Luke 23:45) was understood in the synoptic tradition as a sign of opened divine access — the barrier removed. Hebrews develops this symbolism by identifying the curtain with Christ's flesh (10:20) — the barrier that was the locus of access when torn.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The ark of the covenant (aron ha-berit) was the most sacred object in Israelite religion — the throne-footstool of the divine presence (1 Chr 28:2; Ps 132:7-8), the container of the Torah (Deut 10:5), and the location where God spoke to Moses (Exod 25:22). The first Temple's Most Holy Place contained the ark; the Second Temple had no ark — it had been lost (presumably during the Babylonian conquest), and the Second Temple's Most Holy Place was empty. The Mishnah (Yoma 5:2) notes that the high priest sprinkled blood in the place \"where the ark used to be.\" By Hebrews' time, the Second Temple audience knew the Most Holy Place was empty of the ark — making the argument about Christ's entry into the true heavenly sanctuary even more pointed: the earthly Most Holy Place was already an empty symbol.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The cherubim above the ark (Ex 25:17-22) were understood as the guardians of the divine throne-presence, whose wings formed the seat on which the invisible divine glory rested. The divine title \"the LORD of hosts who is enthroned above the cherubim\" (1 Sam 4:4; 2 Sam 6:2; Isa 37:16) associated the cherubim specifically with divine sovereignty and holy-war power. In Second Temple angelology, cherubim were identified as the highest order of angelic beings — 1 Enoch and the Qumran Songs of the Sabbath Sacrifice describe the cherubim's role in the heavenly throne-room liturgy. The mercy seat (<em>kapporet</em>) where the blood was sprinkled was therefore not merely a ritual object but the earthly focal point of the divine throne — the place where heaven and earth met, and where the blood of atonement was presented to God.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The regular priestly ministry in the outer room (the Holy Place) was the daily routine of Temple service: the lighting of the lamps, the burning of incense morning and evening, and the weekly replacement of the showbread. The Mishnah tractate Tamid describes the daily Temple service in detail: the daily whole-burnt offering (tamid) at dawn and dusk, the incense offering twice daily, the priestly divisions (mishmarot) that rotated service weekly. Twenty-four priestly divisions (1 Chr 24:7-19) took turns serving in the Temple throughout the year. This regular, repeated service was in many ways the heartbeat of Jewish religious life — the daily rhythm by which Israel maintained its relationship with God through the mediating priestly caste.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Holy Spirit's pedagogical communication through the tabernacle structure reflects Hebrews' understanding that the entire Mosaic cult was divinely designed to teach through its limitations. The rabbinic principle that the Torah's commands have both surface and deeper meanings (peshat and derash) enabled interpreters to find theological significance in ritual details. Philo (On the Life of Moses 2.71-108) gave elaborate allegorical explanations for every element of the tabernacle. The specific lesson Hebrews draws — that the curtain-barrier taught that the way to God was not yet open — turns the tabernacle's most prominent limitation into its deepest teaching: the architecture itself was a visual sermon about the inadequacy of the old covenant access to God.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The tabernacle as a \"parable for the present time\" (parabolē eis ton kairon ton enestēkota) reflects the typological hermeneutic that Hebrews shares with Jewish midrashic interpretation, though differently applied. The Qumran pesher method read ancient texts as direct address to the community's present situation; rabbinic midrash found contemporary lessons in every Torah detail. Hebrews reads the tabernacle's structure as an extended parable pointing beyond itself to the Christological fulfillment. The specific point — that the gifts and sacrifices could not perfect the worshipper \"according to conscience\" — addresses the inner-life dimension that the external ritual system acknowledged it could not reach.</p>",
    "10": "<p>\"Food and drink and various ceremonial washings\" describes the external purity regulations that governed access to the sanctuary and participation in communal meals. Leviticus 11-15 covers dietary laws, impurity from bodily discharges, and the purification rituals required after various forms of impurity. The Qumran community intensified these purity requirements considerably, requiring ritual immersion before community meals and maintaining strict dietary separation from outsiders. The Pharisees developed elaborate applications of the purity laws for everyday life (the \"tradition of the elders\" that Jesus debated in Mark 7). Hebrews characterizes these laws as \"external regulations applying until the time of the new order\" — acknowledging their temporary legitimacy while asserting that the time of the new order (diorthōsis) has arrived.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The Yom Kippur blood-ritual that Hebrews compares with Christ's entrance involved the blood of two animals: a bull for the high priest and his household, and a goat for the people (Lev 16:11-15). The high priest entered the Most Holy Place three times: once with the incense pan, once with the bull's blood, once with the goat's blood. Each time, he sprinkled blood on the mercy seat and in front of it. The blood of goats and calves enabled this annual ritual access but required annual repetition — the previous year's sacrifice did not carry over. Hebrews reads this structural limitation as pointing beyond itself: the annual repetition implied incompleteness, and the coming of a sufficient sacrifice would make repetition unnecessary.</p>",
    "14": "<p>\"Christ, who through the eternal Spirit offered himself unblemished to God\" draws on the Day of Atonement requirement that the sacrificial animals be physically unblemished (tamim — Lev 22:19-25). The Mishnah (Parah 1-2) specifies in detail the qualifications for sacrificial animals and the disqualifications for blemish. The high priest's own physical inspection of animals before offering was part of Temple practice. The claim that Christ was \"unblemished\" uses this sacrificial vocabulary to position his self-offering as meeting the highest possible standard of sacrifice — not despite his humanity but in and through it, verified by the \"eternal Spirit\" rather than a priestly inspection.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The concept of covenant mediation had a rich background in Jewish theology. Moses was the mediator (mesitēs) of the Sinai covenant — standing between God and Israel at Sinai when the people feared direct approach (Exod 20:18-21; Deut 5:5; Gal 3:19). The high priest on Yom Kippur mediated between the sinful people and the holy God — his entrance into the Most Holy Place was the annual mediation event on which Israel's covenant standing depended. Angels were sometimes described as mediators between the divine and human realms (Gal 3:19; Heb 2:2). Hebrews' claim that Jesus is the \"mediator of a new covenant\" positions him in this tradition while exceeding it: not merely mediating a covenant but constituting it through his death.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The Greek word <em>diathēkē</em> covered both \"covenant\" (the Septuagintal usage translating Hebrew <em>berit</em>) and \"last will and testament\" (the ordinary Greek legal usage). This double meaning, which Hebrews exploits in 9:16-17, was a feature of the Greek legal environment rather than the Hebrew original. In the Greco-Roman world, a <em>diathēkē</em> (will) was a legal document specifying the distribution of an estate; it became binding only at the testator's death (the lex Julia de legatis of the Roman empire, and Greek equivalent practices). The metaphor works because the new covenant's promised inheritance (the forgiveness, the Spirit, the eschatological rest) could not be distributed until the covenant-maker's death had legally activated the covenant-will.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The legal maxim \"a will is in force only when somebody has died; it never takes effect while the one who made it is living\" reflects standard Hellenistic testamentary law. Papyri from Roman Egypt document wills and their conditions; the requirement that the testator be confirmed dead before distribution could begin was universally understood. In the Greco-Roman context of the letter's audience, this legal principle was as familiar as the equivalent modern legal procedure. Hebrews' application of this principle to the new covenant is a context-specific argument: for readers formed in Hellenistic legal culture, the will-analogy provided an immediately intelligible explanation of why the Messiah's death was not a problem for the covenant but its necessary precondition.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The Exodus 24:3-8 blood-inauguration of the Sinai covenant was a foundational narrative for Jewish understanding of covenant-making through blood. The ceremony (Moses reading the Book of the Covenant, the people's response, the sacrifice, and the blood-sprinkling on the altar and the people) established the pattern: covenants were sealed with blood that bound both parties. The phrase \"the blood of the covenant\" (Exod 24:8) became a technical covenantal formula — quoted directly by Jesus at the Last Supper (Matt 26:28; Mark 14:24) to frame his death as a covenant-inauguration event. For a Jewish audience that understood Exodus 24 as the template for covenant-making, the application of covenant-blood language to Jesus's death was immediately intelligible as a claim that Jesus's death inaugurated the new covenant Jeremiah promised.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The blood-sprinkling ceremony described in Exodus 24:6-8 involved hyssop and scarlet wool (also used in the red heifer ritual, Num 19:6) mixed with water — a composite purification medium. The Mishnah and later rabbinic texts preserve extensive discussion of the precise implements and quantities used. The addition of \"calves and goats\" to Hebrews' account (not in the Exodus text) may reflect liturgical expansion of the ceremony in tradition, or harmonization with the Yom Kippur blood-ritual. The sprinkling of \"the scroll and all the people\" emphasized that both the written law and the human community were encompassed by the covenant-blood — the covenant applied to both the textual document and the embodied people.</p>",
    "20": "<p>\"This is the blood of the covenant, which God has commanded you to keep\" (Exod 24:8) is the formula that Jesus reuses at the Last Supper. The liturgical resonance between the Sinai blood-of-the-covenant and the eucharistic words would be unmistakable to a community that celebrated the Lord's Supper regularly. The Passover Haggadah's retelling of the Exodus events, which the synagogue and Jewish-Christian communities used, kept the Exodus covenant-making in continuous liturgical memory. The Last Supper's explicit connection of Jesus's blood to \"the blood of the covenant\" positioned the Christian meal in direct continuity with and supersession of the Sinai covenant-inauguration.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Moses's sprinkling of the tabernacle and its furnishings with blood (referenced here but not detailed in Exodus 40's account of the tabernacle's erection) reflects a priestly tradition about the comprehensive blood-consecration of sacred objects. Leviticus 8:10-11 describes Moses anointing the tabernacle with oil; later tradition may have incorporated blood-sprinkling into the comprehensive consecration. The point Hebrews makes is that the entire Mosaic system — from the covenant document to the people to the sanctuary and its furnishings — was consecrated through blood. This universal blood-consecration of the old order corresponds to the universal scope of Christ's blood-offering, which consecrates not just the earthly copies but the heavenly originals themselves (v23).</p>",
    "22": "<p>\"Without the shedding of blood there is no forgiveness\" reflects the theological logic underlying the entire Levitical sacrificial system. Leviticus 17:11 states the principle: \"the life of the flesh is in the blood, and I have given it for you on the altar to make atonement for your souls, for it is the blood that makes atonement by the life.\" The life-in-blood principle undergirded the substitutionary logic of sacrifice: the animal's life (blood) substituted for the worshipper's life, absorbing the death-consequence of sin. Philo (On Special Laws 1.198-199) reflects on this principle philosophically. The practical scope of blood-requirement in Leviticus was extensive — purification, ordination, guilt-offerings, sin-offerings all required blood — though Hebrews' \"almost everything\" (schedon) acknowledges the exceptions (fire-purification, water-purification, oil-anointing).</p>",
    "23": "<p>The requirement that the heavenly things themselves be purified with \"better sacrifices\" (plural) addresses the apparent paradox that the heavenly originals need purification. Jewish apocalyptic thought acknowledged that heavenly things could be defiled by human sin: 1 Enoch 9:1-11 describes the archangels presenting the cry of human suffering to God; the heavenly court was understood to be affected by earthly events. The Qumran Rule of the Community (1QS 3:4-9) describes the Spirit of Truth purifying the inner person; purification was a concept that transcended the merely physical. The \"better sacrifices\" (plural, corresponding to the multiple Levitical purification sacrifices) refers to the single sufficient sacrifice of Christ viewed from multiple angles of its comprehensive effect.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Christ's entry into \"heaven itself, to appear in the presence of God on our behalf\" positions him as the permanent Day-of-Atonement high priest. The Yom Kippur structure created one annual moment when the high priest stood in the divine presence as Israel's representative — the rest of the year, Israel approached God only through intermediaries at the outer altar. The priestly blessing (Num 6:22-27), the daily incense, and the showbread maintained continuous symbolic presence, but the Yom Kippur entry was the year's climactic moment of actual representative presence. Hebrews claims that the risen Christ maintains this representative presence permanently — not one day per year but continuously, \"now to appear in the presence of God on our behalf.\"</p>",
    "25": "<p>The contrast between annual entry with \"blood that is not his own\" and Christ's once-for-all entry with his own blood addresses the structural problem of Yom Kippur: the high priest brought animal blood as a substitute for his own life. The prohibition on the high priest bringing his own blood was never a theological question in Levitical practice — the priest was not the sacrifice. The entire design of the Levitical system separated the sacrificer from the sacrifice. Christ's self-offering collapse this separation: the priest becomes the sacrifice. This convergence of priest and victim in one person had no precedent in the Levitical system, making it structurally impossible to accommodate Christ's priesthood within that system.</p>",
    "26": "<p>\"At the culmination of the ages\" (epi synteleia tōn aiōnōn) uses an apocalyptic technical phrase for the end-point of the current age before the new age begins. 4 Ezra 7:113 uses similar language for the eschatological judgment; the Dead Sea Scrolls (1QpHab 7:2; 1QS 4:25) use \"the end of times\" and \"the appointed end\" for the climactic moment toward which the whole of history moves. Hebrews places Jesus's death at exactly this eschatological hinge-point: not just any moment in history but the defining event that marks the transition from the old to the new. The claim that the Messiah appeared \"once for all\" at this moment is both a historical assertion (it happened at a specific time) and an eschatological claim (that time was the decisive turn of the ages).</p>",
    "27": "<p>\"People are destined to die once, and after that to face judgment\" states what was a near-universal conviction in Jewish eschatology, though with important debates about its details. The Pharisees affirmed bodily resurrection and post-mortem judgment (Josephus, Jewish War 2.163; Acts 23:6-8); the Sadducees denied resurrection (Matt 22:23; Josephus, Jewish War 2.165). Wisdom of Solomon 3-5 describes the post-mortem vindication of the righteous who suffered and the condemnation of the wicked who prospered. 4 Ezra 7:32-44 presents an elaborate judgment sequence after death. The aphorism here is not a theological argument but a shared cultural assumption — the one-death / one-judgment structure of human existence is the pattern against which Christ's once-for-all sacrifice is analogized in v28.</p>",
    "28": "<p>\"Christ was sacrificed once to take away the sins of many\" echoes Isaiah 53:12 (\"he bore the sin of many\") from the Servant Song — one of the most debated passages in Second Temple Jewish interpretation. The Targum Jonathan interpreted Isaiah 53 of the nation of Israel rather than an individual servant; other interpretations identified the servant with Moses, or with a martyred righteous figure. The early Christian reading that applied Isaiah 53 to Jesus's death was therefore a specific interpretation in a contested exegetical tradition. The echo of \"the many\" (pollōn) is deliberate: it positions Christ's death as the fulfillment of the Servant's vicarious suffering, resolving the interpretive question of who the Servant was by pointing to the historical event of the crucifixion. \"He will appear a second time\" introduces the parousia expectation that concludes the Yom Kippur typology: after the high priest's entry into the Most Holy Place, the congregation waited anxiously for his exit — his reappearance was the signal that atonement had been accepted.</p>"
  }
}
""")

def main():
    existing = load_comm("mkt-context", "hebrews")
    merge_comm(existing, HEBREWS)
    save_comm("mkt-context", "hebrews", existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f"Hebrews 6-9 mkt-context gaps filled: {len(existing)} chapters, {total} verses written.")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
